# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/fluid-simulation] Fluid animation differs from computational fluid dynamics (CFD) in that fluid animation is used primarily for visual effects, whereas computational fluid dynamics is used to study the behavior of fluids in a scientifically rigorous way.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/fluid-simulation] The development of fluid animation techniques based on the Navier–Stokes equations began in 1996, when Nick Foster and Dimitris Metaxas implemented solutions to 3D Navier-Stokes equations in a computer graphics context, basing their work on a scientific CFD paper by Harlow and Welch from 1965.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/fluid-simulation] Up to that point, a variety of simpler methods had primarily been used, including ad-hoc particle systems, lower dimensional techniques such as height fields, and semi-random turbulent noise fields.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/fluid-simulation] In 1999, Jos Stam published the "Stable Fluids" method, which exploited a semi-Lagrangian advection technique and implicit integration of viscosity to provide unconditionally stable behaviour.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/fluid-simulation] This allowed for much larger time steps and therefore faster simulations.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/fluid-simulation] This general technique was extended by Ronald Fedkiw and co-authors to handle more realistic smoke and fire, as well as complex 3D water simulations using variants of the level-set method.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/fluid-simulation] Some notable academic researchers in this area include Jerry Tessendorf, James F.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/fluid-simulation] O'Brien, Ron Fedkiw, Mark Carlson, Greg Turk, Robert Bridson, Ken Museth, and Jos Stam.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/fluid-simulation] Many 3D computer graphics programs implement fluid animation techniques.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/fluid-simulation] RealFlow is a standalone commercial package that has been used to produce visual effects in movies, television shows, commercials, and games.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/fluid-simulation] RealFlow implements a fluid-implicit particle (FLIP; an extension of the Particle-in-cell method) solver, a hybrid grid, and a particle method that allows for advanced features such as foam and spray.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/fluid-simulation] Maya and Houdini are two other commercial 3D computer graphics programs that allow for fluid animation.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/fluid-simulation] Blender is an open-source 3D computer graphics program that utilized a particle-based Lattice Boltzmann method for animating fluids until the integration of the open-source mantaflow project in 2020 with a wide range of Navier-Stokes solver variants.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/immersed-boundary-method] In computational fluid dynamics, the **immersed boundary method** originally referred to an approach developed by Charles Peskin in 1972 to simulate fluid-structure (fiber) interactions.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/immersed-boundary-method] Treating the coupling of the structure deformations and the fluid flow poses a number of challenging problems for numerical simulations (the elastic boundary changes the flow of the fluid and the fluid moves the elastic boundary simultaneously).
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/immersed-boundary-method] In the immersed boundary method the fluid is represented in an Eulerian coordinate system and the structure is represented in Lagrangian coordinates.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/immersed-boundary-method] The immersed structures are typically represented as a collection of one-dimensional fibers, denoted by $\Gamma$ .
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/immersed-boundary-method] Each fiber can be viewed as a parametric curve $X(s,t)$ where s is the Lagrangian coordinate along the fiber and t is time.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/immersed-boundary-method] The physics of the fiber is represented via a fiber force distribution function $F(s,t)$ .
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/immersed-boundary-method] Spring forces, bending resistance or any other type of behavior can be built into this term.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/immersed-boundary-method] The forcing can be extended to multiple dimensions to model elastic surfaces or three-dimensional solids.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/immersed-boundary-method] where $\Omega$ denotes the entire fluid domain.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/immersed-boundary-method] Discretization of these equations can be done by assuming an Eulerian grid on the fluid and a separate Lagrangian grid on the fiber.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/immersed-boundary-method] Approximations of the Delta distribution by smoother functions will allow us to interpolate between the two grids.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/immersed-boundary-method] Any existing fluid solver can be coupled to a solver for the fiber equations to solve the Immersed Boundary equations.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/immersed-boundary-method] Variants of this basic approach have been applied to simulate a wide variety of mechanical systems involving elastic structures which interact with fluid flows.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/immersed-boundary-method] Since the original development of this method by Peskin, a variety of approaches have been developed.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/immersed-boundary-method] Methods for complicated body shapes include the immersed interface method, the Cartesian grid method, the ghost fluid method and the cut-cell methods categorizing immersed boundary methods into *continuous forcing* and *discrete forcing* methods.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/immersed-boundary-method] In general, for immersed boundary methods and related variants, there is an active research community that is still developing new techniques and related software implementations and incorporating related techniques into simulation packages and CAD engineering software.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/kernel-statistics] The term **kernel** is used in statistical analysis to refer to a window function.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/kernel-statistics] The term "kernel" has several distinct meanings in different branches of statistics.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/kernel-statistics] In statistics, especially in Bayesian statistics, the kernel of a probability density function (pdf) or probability mass function (pmf) is the form of the pdf or pmf in which any factors that are not functions of any of the variables in the domain are omitted.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/kernel-statistics] Note that such factors may well be functions of the parameters of the pdf or pmf.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/kernel-statistics] These factors form part of the normalization factor of the probability distribution, and are unnecessary in many situations.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/kernel-statistics] For example, in pseudo-random number sampling, most sampling algorithms ignore the normalization factor.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/kernel-statistics] In addition, in Bayesian analysis of conjugate prior distributions, the normalization factors are generally ignored during the calculations, and only the kernel considered.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/kernel-statistics] At the end, the form of the kernel is examined, and if it matches a known distribution, the normalization factor can be reinstated.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/kernel-statistics] Otherwise, it may be unnecessary (for example, if the distribution only needs to be sampled from).
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/kernel-statistics] For many distributions, the kernel can be written in closed form, but not the normalization constant.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/kernel-statistics] Note that the factor in front of the exponential has been omitted, even though it contains the parameter $\sigma ^{2}$ , because it is not a function of the domain variable x .
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/kernel-statistics] The kernel of a reproducing kernel Hilbert space is used in the suite of techniques known as kernel methods to perform tasks such as statistical classification, regression analysis, and cluster analysis on data in an implicit space.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/kernel-statistics] This usage is particularly common in machine learning.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/kernel-statistics] In nonparametric statistics, a kernel is a weighting function used in non-parametric estimation techniques.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/kernel-statistics] Kernels are used in kernel density estimation to estimate random variables' density functions, or in kernel regression to estimate the conditional expectation of a random variable.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/kernel-statistics] Kernels are also used in time series, in the use of the periodogram to estimate the spectral density where they are known as window functions.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/kernel-statistics] An additional use is in the estimation of a time-varying intensity for a point process where window functions (kernels) are convolved with time-series data.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/kernel-statistics] Commonly, kernel widths must also be specified when running a non-parametric estimation.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/kernel-statistics] The first requirement ensures that the method of kernel density estimation results in a probability density function.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/kernel-statistics] The second requirement ensures that the average of the corresponding distribution is equal to that of the sample used.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/kernel-statistics] If *K* is a kernel, then so is the function *K** defined by *K**(*u*) = λ*K*(λ*u*), where λ > 0.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/kernel-statistics] This can be used to select a scale that is appropriate for the data.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/kernel-statistics] Several types of kernel functions are commonly used: uniform, triangle, Epanechnikov, quartic (biweight), tricube, triweight, Gaussian, quadratic and cosine.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/kernel-statistics] In the table below, if K is given with a bounded support, then $K(u)=0$ for values of *u* lying outside the support.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/meshfree-methods] In the field of numerical analysis, **meshfree methods** are those that do not require connection between nodes of the simulation domain, i.e. a mesh, but are rather based on interaction of each node with all its neighbors.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/meshfree-methods] As a consequence, original extensive properties such as mass or kinetic energy are no longer assigned to mesh elements but rather to the single nodes.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/meshfree-methods] Meshfree methods enable the simulation of some otherwise difficult types of problems, at the cost of extra computing time and programming effort.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/meshfree-methods] The absence of a mesh allows Lagrangian simulations, in which the nodes can move according to the velocity field.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/meshfree-methods] Numerical methods such as the finite difference method, finite-volume method, and finite element method were originally defined on meshes of data points.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/meshfree-methods] In such a mesh, each point has a fixed number of predefined neighbors, and this connectivity between neighbors can be used to define mathematical operators like the derivative.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/meshfree-methods] These operators are then used to construct the equations to simulate—such as the Euler equations or the Navier–Stokes equations.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/meshfree-methods] If the mesh becomes tangled or degenerate during simulation, the operators defined on it may no longer give correct values.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/meshfree-methods] The mesh may be recreated during simulation (a process called remeshing), but this can also introduce error, since all the existing data points must be mapped onto a new and different set of data points.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/meshfree-methods] Meshfree methods are intended to remedy these problems.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/meshfree-methods] Then we can use these definitions of $u(x,t)$ and its spatial and temporal derivatives to write the equation being simulated in finite difference form, then simulate the equation with one of many finite difference methods.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/meshfree-methods] In this simple example, the steps (here the spatial step h and timestep k ) are constant along all the mesh, and the left and right mesh neighbors of the data value at $x_{i}$ are the values at $x_{i-1}$ and $x_{i+1}$ , respectively.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/meshfree-methods] Generally in finite differences one can allow very simply for steps variable along the mesh, but all the original nodes should be preserved and they can move independently only by deforming the original elements.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/meshfree-methods] If even only two of all the nodes change their order, or even only one node is added to or removed from the simulation, that creates a defect in the original mesh and the simple finite difference approximation can no longer hold.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/meshfree-methods] Smoothed-particle hydrodynamics (SPH), one of the oldest meshfree methods, solves this problem by treating data points as physical particles with mass and density that can move around over time, and carry some value $u_{i}$ with them.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/meshfree-methods] where $m_{i}$ is the mass of particle i , $\rho _{i}$ is the density of particle i , and W is a kernel function that operates on nearby data points and is chosen for smoothness and other useful qualities.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/meshfree-methods] Then we can use these definitions of $u(x,t)$ and its spatial derivatives to write the equation being simulated as an ordinary differential equation, and simulate the equation with one of many numerical methods.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/meshfree-methods] In physical terms, this means calculating the forces between the particles, then integrating these forces over time to determine their motion.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/meshfree-methods] The advantage of SPH in this situation is that the formulae for $u(x,t)$ and its derivatives do not depend on any adjacency information about the particles; they can use the particles in any order, so it doesn't matter if the particles move around or even exchange places.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/meshfree-methods] One disadvantage of SPH is that it requires extra programming to determine the nearest neighbors of a particle.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/meshfree-methods] Since the kernel function W only returns nonzero results for nearby particles within twice the "smoothing length" (because we typically choose kernel functions with compact support), it would be a waste of effort to calculate the summations above over every particle in a large simulation.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/meshfree-methods] So typically SPH simulators require some extra code to speed up this nearest neighbor calculation.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/meshfree-methods] One of the earliest meshfree methods is smoothed particle hydrodynamics, presented in 1977.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/meshfree-methods] Libersky *et al.* were the first to apply SPH in solid mechanics.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/meshfree-methods] The main drawbacks of SPH are inaccurate results near boundaries and tension instability that was first investigated by Swegle.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/meshfree-methods] In the 1990s a new class of meshfree methods emerged based on the Galerkin method.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/meshfree-methods] This first method called the diffuse element method (DEM), pioneered by Nayroles et al., utilized the MLS approximation in the Galerkin solution of partial differential equations, with approximate derivatives of the MLS function.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/meshfree-methods] Thereafter Belytschko pioneered the Element Free Galerkin (EFG) method, which employed MLS with Lagrange multipliers to enforce boundary conditions, higher order numerical quadrature in the weak form, and full derivatives of the MLS approximation which gave better accuracy.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/meshfree-methods] Around the same time, the reproducing kernel particle method (RKPM) emerged, the approximation motivated in part to correct the kernel estimate in SPH: to give accuracy near boundaries, in non-uniform discretizations, and higher-order accuracy in general.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/meshfree-methods] Notably, in a parallel development, the Material point methods were developed around the same time which offer similar capabilities.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/meshfree-methods] Material point methods are widely used in the movie industry to simulate large deformation solid mechanics, such as snow in the movie Frozen.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/meshfree-methods] RKPM and other meshfree methods were extensively developed by Chen, Liu, and Li in the late 1990s for a variety of applications and various classes of problems.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/meshfree-methods] During the 1990s and thereafter several other varieties were developed including those listed below.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/meshfree-methods] The following numerical methods are generally considered to fall within the general class of "meshfree" methods.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/meshfree-methods] The primary areas of advancement in meshfree methods are to address issues with essential boundary enforcement, numerical quadrature, and contact and large deformations.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/meshfree-methods] The common weak form requires strong enforcement of the essential boundary conditions, yet meshfree methods in general lack the Kronecker delta property.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/meshfree-methods] This make essential boundary condition enforcement non-trivial, at least more difficult than the Finite element method, where they can be imposed directly.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/meshfree-methods] Techniques have been developed to overcome this difficulty and impose conditions strongly.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/meshfree-methods] Several methods have been developed to impose the essential boundary conditions weakly, including Lagrange multipliers, Nitche's method, and the penalty method.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/meshfree-methods] As for quadrature, nodal integration is generally preferred which offers simplicity, efficiency, and keeps the meshfree method free of any mesh (as opposed to using Gauss quadrature, which necessitates a mesh to generate quadrature points and weights).
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/meshfree-methods] Nodal integration however, suffers from numerical instability due to underestimation of strain energy associated with short-wavelength modes, and also yields inaccurate and non-convergent results due to under-integration of the weak form.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/meshfree-methods] One major advance in numerical integration has been the development of a stabilized conforming nodal integration (SCNI) which provides a nodal integration method which does not suffer from either of these problems.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/meshfree-methods] The method is based on strain-smoothing which satisfies the first order patch test.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/meshfree-methods] However, it was later realized that low-energy modes were still present in SCNI, and additional stabilization methods have been developed.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/meshfree-methods] This method has been applied to a variety of problems including thin and thick plates, poromechanics, convection-dominated problems, among others.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/meshfree-methods] More recently, a framework has been developed to pass arbitrary-order patch tests, based on a Petrov–Galerkin method.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/meshfree-methods] One recent advance in meshfree methods aims at the development of computational tools for automation in modeling and simulations.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/meshfree-methods] This is enabled by the so-called weakened weak (W2) formulation based on the G space theory.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/meshfree-methods] The W2 formulation offers possibilities to formulate various (uniformly) "soft" models that work well with triangular meshes.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/meshfree-methods] Because a triangular mesh can be generated automatically, it becomes much easier in re-meshing and hence enables automation in modeling and simulation.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/meshfree-methods] In addition, W2 models can be made soft enough (in uniform fashion) to produce upper bound solutions (for force-driving problems).
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/meshfree-methods] Together with stiff models (such as the fully compatible FEM models), one can conveniently bound the solution from both sides.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/meshfree-methods] This allows easy error estimation for generally complicated problems, as long as a triangular mesh can be generated.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/meshfree-methods] Typical W2 models are the Smoothed Point Interpolation Methods (or S-PIM).
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/meshfree-methods] The S-PIM can be node-based (known as NS-PIM or LC-PIM), edge-based (ES-PIM), and cell-based (CS-PIM).
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/meshfree-methods] The NS-PIM was developed using the so-called SCNI technique.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/meshfree-methods] It was then discovered that NS-PIM is capable of producing upper bound solution and volumetric locking free.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/meshfree-methods] The ES-PIM is found superior in accuracy, and CS-PIM behaves in between the NS-PIM and ES-PIM.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/meshfree-methods] Moreover, W2 formulations allow the use of polynomial and radial basis functions in the creation of shape functions (it accommodates the discontinuous displacement functions, as long as it is in G1 space), which opens further rooms for future developments.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/meshfree-methods] The W2 formulation has also led to the development of combination of meshfree techniques with the well-developed FEM techniques, and one can now use triangular mesh with excellent accuracy and desired softness.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/meshfree-methods] A typical such a formulation is the so-called smoothed finite element method (or S-FEM).
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/meshfree-methods] The S-FEM is the linear version of S-PIM, but with most of the properties of the S-PIM and much simpler.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/meshfree-methods] It is a general perception that meshfree methods are much more expensive than the FEM counterparts.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/meshfree-methods] The recent study has found however, some meshfree methods such as the S-PIM and S-FEM can be much faster than the FEM counterparts.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/meshfree-methods] The S-PIM and S-FEM works well for solid mechanics problems.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/meshfree-methods] For CFD problems, the formulation can be simpler, via strong formulation.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/meshfree-methods] A Gradient Smoothing Methods (GSM) has also been developed recently for CFD problems, implementing the gradient smoothing idea in strong form.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/meshfree-methods] The GSM is similar to [FVM], but uses gradient smoothing operations exclusively in nested fashions, and is a general numerical method for PDEs.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/meshfree-methods] Nodal integration has been proposed as a technique to use finite elements to emulate a meshfree behaviour.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/meshfree-methods] However, the obstacle that must be overcome in using nodally integrated elements is that the quantities at nodal points are not continuous, and the nodes are shared among multiple elements.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] In fluid mechanics, **multiphase flow** is the simultaneous flow of materials with two or more thermodynamic phases.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] Virtually all processing technologies from cavitating pumps and turbines to paper-making and the construction of plastics involve some form of multiphase flow.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] It is also prevalent in many natural phenomena.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] These phases may consist of one chemical component (e.g. flow of water and water vapour), or several different chemical components (e.g. flow of oil and water).
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] A phase is classified as *continuous* if it occupies a continually connected region of space (as opposed to *disperse* if the phase occupies disconnected regions of space).
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] The continuous phase may be either gaseous or a liquid.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] The disperse phase can consist of a solid, liquid or gas.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] Two general topologies can be identified: *disperse* flows and *separated* flows.The former consists of finite particles, drops or bubbles distributed within a continuous phase, whereas the latter consists of two or more continuous streams of fluids separated by interfaces.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] The study of multiphase flow is strongly linked to the development of fluid mechanics and thermodynamics.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] A key early discovery was made by Archimedes of Syracuse (250 BCE) who postulated the laws of buoyancy, which became known as the Archimedes' principle – which is used in modelling multiphase flow.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] In the mid-20th century, advances in nucleate boiling were developed and the first two-phase pressure-drop models were formed, primarily for the chemical and process industries.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] In particular, Lockhart and Martinelli (1949) presented a model for frictional pressure drop in horizontal, separated two-phase flow, introducing a parameter that is still utilised today.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] Between 1950 and 1960, intensive work in the aerospace and nuclear sectors triggered further studies into two-phase flow.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] In 1958 one of the earliest systematic studies of two-phase flow was undertaken by Soviet scientist Teletov.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] Baker (1965) conducted studies into vertical flow regimes.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] From the 1970s onwards, multiphase flow especially in the context of the oil industry has been studied extensively due to the increasing dependence of petroleum by the world economy.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] The 1980s saw further modelling of multiphase flow by modelling flow patterns to different pipe inclinations and diameters and different pressures and flows.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] Advancements in computing power in the 1990s allowed for increasingly complex modelling techniques to modelling multiphase flow, flows that were previously limited to one-dimensional problems could be pushed to three-dimensional models.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] Projects to develop multiphase flow metering technology (MFM), used to measure the rate of individual phase flow appeared in the 1990s.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] The impetus behind this technology was a forecasted decline of production from the major North Sea oil fields.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] Oil companies that created early prototypes included BP and Texaco, MFMS have now become ubiquitous and are now the primary metering solution for new-field developments.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] Avalanche on the Alps, fog engulfing the Golden Gate Bridge and sediment being deposited into the Pacific Ocean by the Eel river.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] Multiphase flow occurs regularly in many natural phenomena, and also is well documented and crucial within various industries.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] Sediment transport in rivers is subject to multiphase flow, in which the suspended particles are treated as a disperse second phase which interacts with the continuous fluid phase.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] An example of multiphase flow on a smaller scale would be within porous structures.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] Pore-structure modelling enables the use of Darcy's law to calculate the volumetric flow rate through porous media such as groundwater flow through rock.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] Further examples occur within the bodies of living organisms, such as blood flow (with plasma being the liquid phase and red blood cells constituting the solid phase.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] Also flow within the intestinal tract of the human body, with solid food particles and water flowing simultaneously.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] The large majority of processing technology involves multiphase flow.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] A common example of multiphase flow in industry is a fluidized bed.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] This device combines a solid-liquid mixture and causes it to move like a fluid.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] Further examples include water electrolysis, bubbly flow in nuclear reactors, gas-particle flow in combustion reactors and fiber suspension flows within the pulp and paper industry.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] In oil and gas industries, multiphase flow often implies to simultaneous flow of oil, water and gas.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] The term is also applicable to the properties of a flow in some field where there is a chemical injection or various types of inhibitors.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] In petroleum engineering, drilling fluid consists of a gas-solid phase.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] Furthermore, crude oil during flow through pipelines is a gas-oil-water three phase flow.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] The most common class of multiphase flows are two-phase flows, and these include Gas-Liquid Flow, Gas-Solid Flow, Liquid-Liquid Flow and Liquid-Solid Flow.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] These flows are the most studied, and are of most interest in the context of industry.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] Different patterns of multiphase flow are known as flow regimes.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] Flow patterns in pipes are governed by the diameter of the pipe, the physical properties of the fluids and their flow rates.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] As velocity and gas-liquid ratio is increased, "bubble flow" transitions into "mist flow".
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] At high liquid-gas ratios, liquid forms the continuous phase and at low values it forms the disperse phase.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] In plug and slug flow, gas flows faster than the liquid and the liquid forms a 'slug' which becomes detached and velocity decreases until the next liquid slug catches up.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] In *Vertical flow* axial symmetry exists and flow patterns are more stable.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] However, in regards to slug flow oscillations in this regime can occur.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] Horizontal flow regimes can be applied here, however, we see a more even distribution of particles due to the buoyancy force acting in the direction of the pipe.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] Churn flow occurs when slug flow breaks down, leading to an unstable regime in which there is an oscillatory motion of the liquid.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] Wispy annular flow is characterised by the liquid 'wisps' that exist in the annular flow regime.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] Presumably due to the coalescence of the large concentration of contained droplets in the liquid film covering the pipe.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] Hydraulic transport consists of flows in which solid particles are dispersed in a continuous liquid phase.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] They are often referred to as slurry flows.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] Applications include the transport of coals and ores to the flow of mud.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] Gas–solid two-phase flow widely exists in chemical engineering, power engineering, and metallurgical engineering.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] In order to reduce atmospheric pollution and pipe erosion, improve product quality, and process efficiency, flow parameter measurement of two-phase flow by pneumatic conveying (using pressurised gas to induce flow) is becoming increasingly widespread.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] *Three-phase, gas-liquid-liquid flows:* Mixtures of vapors and two immiscible liquid phases are common in chemical engineering plants.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] Examples are gas-oil-water flows in oil recovery systems and immiscible condensate-vapor flows in steam/hydrocarbon condensing systems.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] Further examples lie in the flow of oil, water and natural gas.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] These flows can occur in condensation or evaporation of liquid mixtures (e.g. the condensation or evaporation of steam or hydrocarbons).
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] *Solid-liquid-liquid flows:* An example is sand mixing with oil and water in a pipeline.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] Multiphase flows are not restricted to only three phases.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] An example of *a four phase flow* system would be that of direct-contact freeze crystallization in which, for example, butane liquid is injected into solution from which the crystals are to be formed, and freezing occurs as a result of the evaporation of the liquid butane.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] In this case, the four phases are, respectively, butane liquid, butane vapor, solute phase and crystalline (solid) phase.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] Due to the presence of multiple phases, there are considerable complications in describing and quantifying the nature of the flow compared with conditions of single phase flow.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] Velocity distribution is difficult to calculate due to the lack of knowledge of the velocities of each phase at a single point.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] There are several ways to model multiphase flow, including the Euler-Langrange method, where the fluid phase is treated as a continuum by solving the Navier-Stokes equations.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] The dispersed phase is solved by tracking a large number of disperse particles, bubbles or droplets.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] The dispersed phase can exchange momentum, mass and energy with the fluid phase.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] Euler-Euler two phase flow is characterised by the volume-averaged mass conservation equation for each phase.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] In this model, the disperse and continuous phase are treated as fluids.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] The concept of a volume fraction is introduced for each phase, discussed in the parameter section below.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] The most simple method to categorize continuous multiphase flows is to consider treat each phase independently.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] This concept is known as the homogeneous flow model first proposed by Soviet scientists in the 1960s.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] Where $\ G$ = mass flow rate of a single phase, Δ = change in quantity, m = Mass of that phase t = time and the dot above m being a time derivative.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] Where Q = volumetric flow rate of a single phase, V = Volume.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] The variables stated above can be input into the below parameters that are important in the description of multiphase flow.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] In wellbore multiphase flow the mass flow rate, volumetric fraction and velocity of each phase are important parameters.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] A flow through a conduit of constant cross-sectional area is considered to be under steady-state conditions when its velocity and pressure may vary from point to point but do not change with time.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] If these conditions are variable with time then the flow is known as *transient.* The gas phase most commonly flows at a higher velocity than the liquid phase, this is due to the lower density and viscosity.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] The volumetric flow rate and fluid motion, in general, is driven by different forces acting on fluid elements.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] There are five forces that affect flow rate, each of these forces can be categorised in three different types; line, surface and volume.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] Volume forces act on an element proportional to the volume ( $V\propto L^{3}$ ).
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] Where P = pressure, ρ = mass density, Δ = change in quantity, σ = surface tension, μ = Dynamic viscosity, A = area g = acceleration due to gravity, L = linear dimension, V = volume, U = velocity of continuous phase.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] The pressure force acts on an area or surface elements and accelerates the fluid in the downwards direction of the pressure gradient.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] The pressure difference between the beginning and the end of the pressure gradient is known as the pressure drop.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] The Darcy-Weisbach equation can be utilised to calculate pressure drop in a channel.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] The viscous force acts on a surface or area element and tends to make the flow uniform by diminishing velocity differences between phases, effectively opposes flow and lessens flow rate.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] This is evident in comparisons between high viscosity oil mixtures in comparison with low viscosity mixtures, where the higher viscosity oil moves slower.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] The inertia force is a volume force, which retains the direction and the magnitude of the motion.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] It is equivalent to the magnitude of the mass of the element multiplied by its acceleration.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] Acceleration is defined in this case as $U^{2}L^{-1}$ , due to the linear dimension L being proportional to time.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] Higher inertia forces lead to turbulence, whereas lower inertia results in laminar flow.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] The buoyancy force represents the net action of gravity whilst the density is non-uniform.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] The surface-tension force acts on a line or curve element and minimizes the surface area of the interface - this force is specific to gas-liquid or liquid-liquid flows.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] This number predicts whether flow in each phase is either turbulent or laminar.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] At low Reynolds numbers, flow tends towards laminar flow, whereas at high numbers turbulence results from differences in fluid speed.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] In general, laminar flow occurs when Re < 2300 and turbulent flow occurs when Re >4000.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] In the interval, both laminar and turbulent flows are possible and these are called transition flows.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] This number is dependent on geometry of the flow.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] For a mixture of oil and water flowing at high velocity it is most common to form a dispersed bubble type flow.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] Turbulent flow consists of eddies of different size range.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] Eddies that have larger size than droplets, transport these droplets through the flow field.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] Eddies, which are smaller or equal to the size of the droplets, cause droplet deformation and break-up.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] It can be viewed as eddies collide with droplets and break them if they have sufficient energy to overcome the droplets internal forces.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] At the same time, turbulent flow induces droplet-droplet interaction, which is important for the coalescence mechanism.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] When two droplets collide, this may lead to coalescence, resulting in a bigger droplet size.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] The Euler number describes the relationship between the pressure and inertial forces.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] It is used to characterise energy losses in the flow.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] A completely friction-less flow is represented by an Euler number of 1.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] This number is important when the pressure force is dominant.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] Examples include, flow through pipes, flow over submerged bodies and flow of water through orifices.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] The Froude number is the ratio of inertia against gravity.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] When Fr < 1, small surface waves move upstream, Fr > 1 they will be carried downstream and when Fr = 0 the velocity is equal to the surface waves.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] This number is relevant when gravitational force is predominant in the fluid motion.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] For example, open channel flow, wave motion in the ocean, forces on bridge piers and offshore structures.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] The Eötvös number defines the ratio of buoyancy compared with surface tension forces.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] A high value for this number indicates that the system is relatively unaffected by surface tension effects.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] A low value indicates that surface tension dominates.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] The Weber number determines the relationship between the inertial force and surface tension.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] It also determines the droplet size of the disperse phase.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] This number is used extensively in flow regime maps.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] The influence of pipe diameter is well understood through the Weber number.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] An inertia dominated regime with annular flow.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] Transitional regime with a frothy slug-annular flow.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] The transition from frothy slug-annular flow to fully developed annular flow occurs at We = 20.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] The Capillary number can be defined using the Weber number and the Reynolds number.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] It is the relative importance of viscous forces relative to surface forces.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] In microchannel flows, the capillary number plays a critical role as both surface tension and viscous forces are important.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] In enhanced oil recovery operations, capillary number is an important number to consider.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] Whilst capillary number is higher, viscous forces dominate and the effect of interface tension between fluids in rock pores are reduced thereby augmenting recovery.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/multiphase-flow] In typical reservoir conditions, capillary number varies from 10−8 to 10−2.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] Smoothed-particle hydrodynamics is being increasingly used to model fluid motion as well.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] This is due to several benefits over traditional grid-based techniques.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] First, SPH guarantees conservation of mass without extra computation since the particles themselves represent mass.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] Second, SPH computes pressure from weighted contributions of neighboring particles rather than by solving linear systems of equations.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] Finally, unlike grid-based techniques, which must track fluid boundaries, SPH creates a free surface for two-phase interacting fluids directly since the particles represent the denser fluid (usually water) and empty space represents the lighter fluid (usually air).
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] For these reasons, it is possible to simulate fluid motion using SPH in real time.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] However, both grid-based and SPH techniques still require the generation of renderable free surface geometry using a polygonization technique such as metaballs and marching cubes, point splatting, or 'carpet' visualization.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] For gas dynamics it is more appropriate to use the kernel function itself to produce a rendering of gas column density (e.g., as done in the SPLASH visualisation package).
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] One drawback over grid-based techniques is the need for large numbers of particles to produce simulations of equivalent resolution.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] In the typical implementation of both uniform grids and SPH particle techniques, many voxels or particles will be used to fill water volumes that are never rendered.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] However, accuracy can be significantly higher with sophisticated grid-based techniques, especially those coupled with particle methods (such as particle level sets), since it is easier to enforce the incompressibility condition in these systems.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] SPH for fluid simulation is being used increasingly in real-time animation and games where accuracy is not as critical as interactivity.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] Smoothed-particle hydrodynamics's adaptive resolution, numerical conservation of physically conserved quantities, and ability to simulate phenomena covering many orders of magnitude make it ideal for computations in theoretical astrophysics.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] Simulations of galaxy formation, star formation, stellar collisions, supernovae and meteor impacts are some of the wide variety of astrophysical and cosmological uses of this method.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] SPH is used to model hydrodynamic flows, including possible effects of gravity.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] Incorporating other astrophysical processes which may be important, such as radiative transfer and magnetic fields is an active area of research in the astronomical community, and has had some limited success.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] Libersky and Petschek extended SPH to Solid Mechanics.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] The main advantage of SPH in this application is the possibility of dealing with larger local distortion than grid-based methods.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] This feature has been exploited in many applications in Solid Mechanics: metal forming, impact, crack growth, fracture, fragmentation, etc.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] Another important advantage of meshfree methods in general, and of SPH in particular, is that mesh dependence problems are naturally avoided given the meshfree nature of the method.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] In particular, mesh alignment is related to problems involving cracks and it is avoided in SPH due to the isotropic support of the kernel functions.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] However, classical SPH formulations suffer from tensile instabilities and lack of consistency.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] Over the past years, different corrections have been introduced to improve the accuracy of the SPH solution, leading to the RKPM by Liu et al.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] Randles and Libersky and Johnson and Beissel tried to solve the consistency problem in their study of impact phenomena.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] Dyka et al. and Randles and Libersky introduced the stress-point integration into SPH and Ted Belytschko et al. showed that the stress-point technique removes the instability due to spurious singular modes, while tensile instabilities can be avoided by using a Lagrangian kernel.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] Many other recent studies can be found in the literature devoted to improve the convergence of the SPH method.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] Recent improvements in understanding the convergence and stability of SPH have allowed for more widespread applications in Solid Mechanics.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] The Smoothed-Particle Hydrodynamics (SPH) method works by dividing the fluid into a set of discrete moving elements $i,j$ , referred to as particles.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] These particles interact through a kernel function with characteristic radius known as the "smoothing length", typically represented in equations by h .
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] This means that the physical quantity of any particle can be obtained by summing the relevant properties of all the particles that lie within the range of the kernel, the latter being used as a weighting function W .
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] The error in making the above approximation is order $h^{2}$ .
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] where the summation over j includes all particles in the simulation. $V_{j}$ is the volume of particle j , $A_{j}$ is the value of the quantity A for particle j and ${\boldsymbol {r}}$ denotes position.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] where $m_{j}=\rho _{j}V_{j}$ denotes the particle mass and $\rho _{j}$ the particle density, while $W_{ij}=W_{ji}$ is a short notation for $W(|{\boldsymbol {r}}_{i}-{\boldsymbol {r}}_{j}|,h)$ .
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] The error done in approximating the integral by a discrete sum depends on h , on the particle size (i.e. $V_{j}^{1/d}$ , d being the space dimension), and on the particle arrangement in space.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] The latter effect is still poorly known.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] Kernel functions commonly used include the Gaussian function, the quintic spline and the Wendland $C^{2}$ kernel.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] The latter two kernels are compactly supported (unlike the Gaussian, where there is a small contribution at any finite distance away), with support proportional to h .
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] This has the advantage of saving computational effort by not including the relatively minor contributions from distant particles.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] Although the size of the smoothing length can be fixed in both space and time, this does not take advantage of the full power of SPH.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] By assigning each particle its own smoothing length and allowing it to vary with time, the resolution of a simulation can be made to automatically adapt itself depending on local conditions.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] For example, in a very dense region where many particles are close together, the smoothing length can be made relatively short, yielding high spatial resolution.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] Conversely, in low-density regions where individual particles are far apart and the resolution is low, the smoothing length can be increased, optimising the computation for the regions of interest.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] where $\nabla W_{ij}=-\nabla W_{ji}$ is the gradient of $W_{ij}$ with respect to ${\boldsymbol {r}}_{i}$ .
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] This operator gives an SPH approximation of $\nabla \cdot \mathbf {v}$ at the particle i for a given set of particles with given masses $m_{j}$ , positions $\left\{\mathbf {r} _{j}\right\}$ and velocities $\left\{\mathbf {v} _{j}\right\}$ .
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] This property leads to nice conservation properties.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] Notice also that this choice leads to a symmetric divergence operator and antisymmetric gradient.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] Although there are several ways of discretizing the pressure gradient in the Euler equations, the above antisymmetric form is the most acknowledged one.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] It supports strict conservation of linear and angular momentum.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] This means that a force that is exerted on particle i by particle j equals the one that is exerted on particle j by particle i including the sign change of the effective direction, thanks to the antisymmetry property $\nabla W_{ij}=-\nabla W_{ji}$ .
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] Nevertheless, other operators have been proposed, which may perform better numerically or physically.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] For instance, one drawback of these operators is that while the divergence $\operatorname {D}$ is zero-order consistent (i.e. yields zero when applied to a constant vector field), it can be seen that the gradient $\operatorname {\mathbf {G} }$ is not.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] Several techniques have been proposed to circumvent this issue, leading to renormalized operators (see e.g.).
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] where $e_{j}$ is the particle specific internal energy.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] where the chain rule has been used, since $e_{j}$ depends on $\rho _{j}$ , and the latter, on the position of the particles.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] which is the SPH momentum equation already mentioned, where we recognize the $\operatorname {\mathbf {G} }$ operator.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] This explains why linear momentum is conserved, and allows conservation of angular momentum and energy to be conserved as well.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] From the work done in the 80's and 90's on numerical integration of point-like particles in large accelerators, appropriate time integrators have been developed with accurate conservation properties on the long term; they are called symplectic integrators.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] where $\Delta t$ is the time step, superscripts stand for time iterations while ${\boldsymbol {a}}_{i}$ is the particle acceleration, given by the right-hand side of the momentum equation.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] Other symplectic integrators exist (see the reference textbook).
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] It is recommended to use a symplectic (even low-order) scheme instead of a high order non-symplectic scheme, to avoid error accumulation after many iterations.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] Integration of density has not been studied extensively (see below for more details).
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] Symplectic schemes are conservative but explicit, thus their numerical stability requires stability conditions, analogous to the Courant-Friedrichs-Lewy condition (see below).
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] In case the SPH convolution shall be practiced close to a boundary, i.e. closer than *s* · *h*, then the integral support is truncated.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] where B(**r**) is the compact support ball centered at **r**, with radius *s* · *h*, and Ω(**r**) denotes the part of the compact support inside the computational domain, Ω ∩ B(**r**).
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] Hence, imposing boundary conditions in SPH is completely based on approximating the second integral on the right hand side.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] Several techniques has been introduced in the past to model boundaries in SPH.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] This is a popular approach when free-surface is considered in monophase simulations.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] The main benefit of this boundary condition is its obvious simplicity.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] However, several consistency issues shall be considered when this boundary technique is applied.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] That's in fact a heavy limitation on its potential applications.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] Probably the most popular methodology, or at least the most traditional one, to impose boundary conditions in SPH, is Fluid Extension technique.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] Such technique is based on populating the compact support across the boundary with so-called ghost particles, conveniently imposing their field values.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] Along this line, the integral neglect methodology can be considered as a particular case of fluid extensions, where the field, A, vanish outside the computational domain.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] The main benefit of this methodology is the simplicity, provided that the boundary contribution is computed as part of the bulk interactions.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] Also, this methodology has been deeply analyzed in the literature.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] On the other hand, deploying ghost particles in the truncated domain is not a trivial task, such that modelling complex boundary shapes becomes cumbersome.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] The 2 most popular approaches to populate the empty domain with ghost particles are Mirrored-Particles and Fixed-Particles.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] The newest Boundary technique is the Boundary Integral methodology.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] with ***n**j* the normal of the generic *j*-th boundary element.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] The surface term can be also solved considering a semi-analytic expression.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] Another way to determine the density is based on the SPH smoothing operator itself.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] Therefore, the density is estimated from the particle distribution utilizing the SPH interpolation.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] To overcome undesired errors at the free surface through kernel truncation, the density formulation can again be integrated in time.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] The weakly compressible SPH in fluid dynamics is based on the discretization of the Navier–Stokes equations or Euler equations for compressible fluids.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] To close the system, an appropriate equation of state is utilized to link pressure p and density $\rho$ .
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] Generally, the so-called Cole equation (sometimes mistakenly referred to as the "Tait equation") is used in SPH.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] where $\rho _{0}$ is the reference density and c the speed of sound.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] For water, $\gamma =7$ is commonly used.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] The background pressure $p_{0}$ is added to avoid negative pressure values.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] Real nearly incompressible fluids such as water are characterized by very high speeds of sound of the order $10^{3}\mathrm {m/s}$ .
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] Hence, pressure information travels fast compared to the actual bulk flow, which leads to very small Mach numbers M .
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] where $\rho$ is the density change and v the velocity vector.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] In practice a value of c smaller than the real one is adopted to avoid time steps too small in the time integration scheme.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] Generally a numerical speed of sound is adopted such that density variation smaller than 1% are allowed.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] This is the so-called weak-compressibility assumption.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] where the maximum velocity $v_{\text{max}}$ needs to be estimated, for e.g. by Torricelli's law or an educated guess.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] Usually the weakly-compressible schemes are affected by a high-frequency spurious noise on the pressure and density fields.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] This phenomenon is caused by the nonlinear interaction of acoustic waves and by fact that the scheme is explicit in time and centered in space .
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] Through the years, several techniques have been proposed to get rid of this problem.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] 3. the schemes that employ Riemann solvers to model the particle interaction.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] The schemes of the first group apply a filter directly on the density field to remove the spurious numerical noise.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] The most used filters are the MLS (moving least squares) and the Shepard filter which can be applied at each time step or every n time steps.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] The more frequent is the use of the filtering procedure, the more regular density and pressure fields are obtained.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] On the other hand, this leads to an increase of the computational costs.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] In long time simulations, the use of the filtering procedure may lead to the disruption of the hydrostatic pressure component and to an inconsistency between the global volume of fluid and the density field.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] Further, it does not ensure the enforcement of the dynamic free-surface boundary condition.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] The first schemes that adopted such an approach were described in Ferrari and in Molteni where the diffusive term was modeled as a Laplacian of the density field.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] A similar approach was also used in Fatehi and Manzari .
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] In Antuono et al. a correction to the diffusive term of Molteni was proposed to remove some inconsistencies close to the free-surface.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] In this case the adopted diffusive term is equivalent to a high-order differential operator on the density field.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] The scheme is called δ-SPH and preserves all the conservation properties of the SPH without diffusion (e.g., linear and angular momenta, total energy, see ) along with a smooth and regular representation of the density and pressure fields.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] In the third group there are those SPH schemes which employ numerical fluxes obtained through Riemann solvers to model the particle interactions.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] For an SPH method based on Riemann solvers, an inter-particle Riemann problem is constructed along a unit vector $\mathbf {e} _{ij}=-\mathbf {r} _{ij}/r_{ij}$ pointing from particle i to particle j .
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] In this Riemann problem the initial left and right states are on particles i and j , respectively.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] The solution of the Riemann problem results in three waves emanating from the discontinuity.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] Two waves, which can be shock or rarefaction wave, traveling with the smallest or largest wave speed.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] This indicates that the inter-particle average velocity and pressure are simply replaced by the solution of the Riemann problem.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] By comparing both it can be seen that the intermediate velocity and pressure from the inter-particle averages amount to implicit dissipation, i.e. density regularization and numerical viscosity, respectively.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] Note that $\beta$ ensures that there is no dissipation when the fluid is under the action of an expansion wave, i.e. $U_{L}<U_{R}$ , and use modulate dissipation when the fluid is under the action of a compression wave, i.e. $U_{L}\geq U_{R}$ .
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] Also note that the dissipation introduced by the intermediate velocity is not limited.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] In general, the description of hydrodynamic flows require a convenient treatment of diffusive processes to model the viscosity in the Navier–Stokes equations.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] It needs special consideration because it involves the Laplacian differential operator.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] Since the direct computation does not provide satisfactory results, several approaches to model the diffusion have been proposed.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] Introduced by Monaghan and Gingold the artificial viscosity was used to deal with high Mach number fluid flows.
[src:smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics/smoothed-particle-hydrodynamics] Here, $\alpha$ is controlling a volume viscosity while $\beta$ acts similar to the Neumann Richtmeyr artificial viscosity.
